\document=red if you need to print text in over seven lines then you need to use the \count5 counter instead of the \lcctr counter. This is used in this instance to indicate that the counters are not modifiable and must be replenished from outside. The main feature of the application is that it prints a percentage of the total amount of valid questions from the main question and above. The number of questions marked is stored in the \count1 counter and the number of valid questions in the \count5 counter. A valid question is one for which the question is currently marked (i.e. the question is marked at the top of the page). The printer takes two counters instead of one. This is because of the way the counters are used (i.e. one counter is used for counting the number of questions and the other counter is used for marking the questions). It would be necessary to have two counters for this particular application, but the combination of the two counters would allow one to print a percentage as desired. There would still be the need to calculate the number of valid questions from the main question and therefore the \count5 and \count1 counters could not be eliminated in this particular application. ))*)
