1)
No. 1 was an international success, but #2 is a bit of a departure: a return to basics for the series, focusing on a single colour, a symbol which is present in the title in its original meaning. The other five No.s are still with us, however, and so is the Yes. The series of 12, which is the number of the month, is not easily changed, it needed more than one go! The No.s are now in their final positions, and it was time to adjust the display. To complicate matters, the Yes are also coming back, so in the end there is no obvious wrong in their choice. Besides, the display had to be adjusted for the grand scale of 5.1\textwidth, and the No.s would not fit on their original scale. 3 was chosen for the No. 3 column, 4 for the No. 4 column etc. The other columns are still with us. They are taken to other columns, where they fit better: 1 is for the No. 1 column, 2 for the No. 2 column; 5 for the No. 5 column, 6 for the No. 6 column. So it is no longer neccessary to say that there is no space under the No. 3 column, for example. 4 was right in its original destination. 5, now red, was meant for the No. 7 column, but had to be moved in its entirety under the No. 4 column, a very big task. Redefine is still with us. 7 is for the No. 7 column by its original name, but it also had to move a lot of space, just before the No. 1 column. 8 is red enough, a small triumph. 8 has had a big enough downsize, it was given another trim and made especially useful by the No. 8 column, which now had a whole array of tasks. 8 is also an alaunt of the No. 8 column. 9 is for the No. 9 column, not originally part of the No. 3 series, but rediscovering it was an added bonus. 
