\documentclass[red,shift=1.33,nonstop]{review}   #1,1-1,1-1, meaning=green environment, colours=blue!30:demand and defining, text=white, text width=21\cm, top color=purple!50!black, bottom color=blue!30!black, middle color=blue!20!white. The demand for ad space isforever, and therefore the supply has to compete with itself. A 24/7 newsfeed is one option for this. Hence the use of an infinite loop is vital. Then again, the description has to be continuous. Otherwise the inference loop will be terminated before the ad finally appears. So the real trick is to generate the ad continuously, so that it appears in the background at all times, no matter what the viewer does. This can be done with a suitable banner adaption, suitable in this case because the demand is global and without end. So we have to create a loop that changes thebanner ad dynamically. This also changes the size of the banner and that is what we want. So we have to create a larger banner that also changes its size. A solution is to use a real-time display, such as the news feed, and use that for the banner.   A second option is to use a fixed banner, such as an banner that changes in size according to the hours of the day. In our case this is the case. The solution is to use an animation that changes the banner from 0 to 100 in 20 minutes. This means that the banner always changes in size and is always in the 0-100 range. This is what the animation does: it starts from the beginning (0) and goes through the full 100. A good deal of the fun of the animation is that it is a real-time display, so the changes are in real-time and therefore appear to be ad hoc. 2. Adjust the size of the banner: The fixed banner size also means that the quality of the animation is reduced if the original animation was done in full size. So a solution would be to reduce the banner size proportionately. A good idea is therefore to define a smaller banner and then scale the animation to fit the banner size. 3. Avoid clipping: one of the side effects of the animation is that the ad is clipped. So the solution is to avoid clipping and to use spread the ad across the whole banner. One way to do this is to make the ad non-clipping and thus change the size of the banner. 4. Be aware of the effect of clipping: there is the ad viewer who wants to ignore parts of the ad that he or she does not want to see. So the solution is to make the whole ad non-clipping, thus making parts of the ad that viewers ignore can be hidden. 5. For a truly continuous banner the solution is to generate the ad from some continuous function, such as an polar angle. A solution is to simply use a loop that generates the ad from 0,0 to 180 degrees.   11/2/7 = 33 3/2 7 = 11
